b'' b'' b'i recently heard of a mental disorder called obsessive compulsive' b'disorder. what is it? what causes it? could it be caused by a' b'nervous breakdown?' b'' b'obesssive compulsive disorder (not to be confused with obsessive compulsive' b'_personality_ disorder is an acute anxiety disorder characterized by' b'either obsessions (persistent intrusive thoughts that cause anxiety when' b'not entertained), or compulsions (repetitive, ritualistic actions that' b'similarly cause intense psychological discomfort when resisted).' b'' b'ocd is often associated with certain forms of depression.' b'' b'examples of obsessive thoughts are repeated impulses to kill a loved' b'one (though not accompanied by anger), or a religious person having' b'recurrent blasphemous thoughts. generally, the individual attempts to ignore' b'or suppress the intrusive thoughts by engaging in other activities.' b'the individual realizes that the thoughts originate from the own mind, rather' b'than being from an external source.' b'' b'examples of compulsive actions are constant repetitive hand washing,' b'or other activity that is not realistically related to alleviating a' b'source of the anxiety.' b'' b'in ocd, the obsessions or compulsions are highly distressing to the' b'individual, take an hour or more per day, and significantly impair their' b'daily routine and social relationships.' b'' b'treatments include psychotherapy, behavioral methods, and sometimes' b'certain anti-depressants which have recently been found effective in alleviating' b'obsessions and compulsions.' b'' b'the standard diagnostic code for ocd, if you want to look it up in the' b'dsm-iii manual of psychiatric diagnosis is b'' b'kind regards,' b'' b'todd' b'+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'| digital equipment corporation\t\t b'| philadelphia, pa. usa b'| "(a word is) the skin of a living thought" olliver wendell holmes, jr. b'+-----------------------------------------